const UNIT = {
  "gradeLevel": "10",
  "subject": "Physics",
  "strand": "Strand 1.0: Mechanics and Thermal Physics",
  "substrand": "Sub-Strand 1.4: Temperature and Thermal Expansion",
  "totalDuration": "6 lessons × 40 minutes = 240 minutes total",
  "content": "• Temperature as a measure of the degree of hotness or coldness of a body\n• Thermometric properties and types of thermometers (liquid-in-glass, clinical, thermocouple)\n• Temperature scales: Celsius, Kelvin, and conversion between scales\n• Linear expansion of solids: coefficient of linear expansivity (α) and the formula ΔL = αL₀ΔT\n• Applications and effects of linear expansion (railway tracks, bridges, overhead cables, bimetallic strips)\n• Superficial (area) expansion of solids and the relationship to linear expansivity\n• Volumetric (cubical) expansion of solids, liquids, and gases\n• Anomalous expansion of water and its significance in aquatic ecosystems\n• Real and apparent expansion of liquids\n• Applications of thermal expansion (thermostats, riveting, fitting of metal tyres, expansion joints on Kenyan roads and bridges)",
  "learningOutcomes": "By the end of the sub-strand, the learner should be able to:\na) explain temperature as a measure of the degree of hotness or coldness of a body,\nb) describe the working principles of different types of thermometers and their thermometric properties,\nc) convert temperature values between Celsius and Kelvin scales,\nd) determine the linear, superficial, and volumetric expansion of solids using relevant formulae,\ne) investigate the expansion of liquids and distinguish between real and apparent expansion,\nf) explain the anomalous expansion of water and its importance to aquatic life in Kenyan lakes such as Lake Victoria,\ng) apply knowledge of thermal expansion to explain real-life situations such as expansion joints on Kenyan roads and bridges, bimetallic strips in thermostats, and the bursting of sealed containers,\nh) appreciate the role of thermal expansion in engineering design and environmental systems.",
  "coreCompetencies": "• Communication and Collaboration: developed as learners work in groups to design and conduct experiments on thermal expansion of solids and liquids, share findings, and present conclusions to the class using locally available materials such as metal rods and water-filled bottles.\n• Critical Thinking and Problem Solving: developed as learners analyse why a sealed glass bottle filled with water cracks when frozen, apply expansion formulae to calculate changes in dimension, and evaluate how engineers account for thermal expansion in construction of roads and railway lines in Kenya.\n• Learning to Learn: developed as learners independently research applications of thermal expansion in everyday Kenyan contexts (e.g., bimetallic strip thermostats, expansion joints on the Nairobi–Mombasa highway) and reflect on how their mental models change across the lesson sequence.\n• Digital Literacy: developed as learners use digital simulations and videos to visualise molecular behaviour during heating and cooling where physical experiments have limitations, and to record and analyse experimental data.",
  "values": "• Responsibility: the learner handles laboratory equipment carefully and cleans up after experiments, demonstrating personal accountability for the shared learning environment.\n• Respect: the learner listens to and values the contributions of group members when discussing observations on thermal expansion, appreciating that peers may arrive at explanations through different reasoning paths.\n• Unity: the learner collaborates with classmates from diverse backgrounds during group investigations, recognising that shared effort produces stronger scientific understanding.\n• Social Justice: the learner reflects on how communities living near Kenyan lakes (e.g., Lake Turkana, Lake Victoria) are affected by temperature-driven water level and density changes, connecting physics to environmental equity.",
  "sep": "• SEP 1 – Asking Questions and Defining Problems: embedded in Lesson 1 when learners observe the cracked frozen bottle and generate testable questions about why water expands on freezing and what variables affect the degree of expansion in different materials.\n• SEP 2 – Developing and Using Models: embedded throughout the unit as learners build and iteratively revise particle-level diagrams and macroscopic expansion models to explain linear, superficial, volumetric, and anomalous expansion.\n• SEP 3 – Planning and Carrying Out Investigations: embedded in Lessons 2–4 as learners design controlled experiments to measure linear expansion of metal rods and volumetric expansion of water, identifying variables and selecting appropriate measuring instruments.\n• SEP 4 – Analysing and Interpreting Data: embedded in Lessons 3–4 as learners tabulate, graph, and interpret expansion data, calculating coefficients of linear expansivity and identifying anomalous expansion of water from temperature–volume graphs.\n• SEP 6 – Constructing Explanations and Designing Solutions: embedded in Lessons 5–6 as learners construct evidence-based explanations for the anchoring phenomenon and propose engineering design solutions (e.g., gap sizing in railway tracks or road expansion joints) that account for thermal expansion.\n• SEP 8 – Obtaining, Evaluating, and Communicating Information: embedded in Lessons 5–6 as learners research real-world Kenyan applications of thermal expansion, evaluate source credibility, and communicate findings through annotated diagrams and class presentations.",
  "pcis": "• Environmental Education: learners explore the anomalous expansion of water and its role in sustaining aquatic life in Kenyan freshwater bodies (Lake Victoria, Lake Naivasha), connecting thermal physics to ecosystem health and environmental conservation.\n• Safety: learners are guided on the dangers of sealing heated containers (e.g., sealed sufuria lids, bottled water left in a hot matatu) and appreciate the importance of pressure-relief design in everyday Kenyan household and industrial contexts.\n• Life Skills – Critical Thinking and Problem Solving: learners apply thermal expansion concepts to evaluate the safety and efficiency of infrastructure such as the Standard Gauge Railway (SGR) expansion joints and concrete road joints on the Thika Superhighway.\n• STEM Integration: learners connect physics principles to engineering and construction careers relevant to Kenya's Vision 2030 infrastructure projects, including road building, bridge construction, and industrial manufacturing.",
  "careers": "• Civil and Structural Engineer: this sub-strand directly connects to the design of expansion joints in roads, bridges, and buildings — critical skills for Kenya's ongoing infrastructure development under Vision 2030.\n• Mechanical Engineer: learners see how coefficients of thermal expansion govern the design of engines, pipelines, and machinery components used in industries across Nairobi's Industrial Area and Mombasa's port.\n• Meteorologist / Climatologist: understanding temperature scales and thermal behaviour of materials underpins weather forecasting and climate modelling, relevant to Kenya Meteorological Department careers.\n• Medical Professional (Clinical Thermometry): the study of thermometers and temperature scales connects to the use of clinical thermometers and patient temperature monitoring in Kenyan hospitals and clinics.\n• Materials Scientist / Manufacturer: knowledge of expansion properties of solids and liquids is essential for selecting materials in Kenyan manufacturing industries, including metal fabrication and glass production.",
  "focus": "This unit investigates how temperature changes cause matter to expand or contract, anchored in the puzzling real-world observation of a water-filled glass bottle cracking after being placed in a freezer. Learners move from qualitative observations of expansion phenomena to quantitative application of linear, superficial, and volumetric expansion formulae, culminating in evidence-based explanations of both ordinary and anomalous thermal behaviour. Throughout the six lessons, Kenyan infrastructure examples — SGR rail joints, Thika Superhighway expansion gaps, bimetallic thermostats in local appliances — ground abstract physics concepts in familiar, meaningful contexts.",
  "phenomenon": "ANCHORING PHENOMENON — The Cracked Frozen Bottle:\nA learner fills a clean 500 ml glass bottle completely to the brim with water, seals it tightly with a metal cap, and places it in a freezer overnight. The next morning the bottle is cracked — in some cases shattered — and a bulging column of ice protrudes where the cap once sat. This is puzzling because learners' everyday experience tells them that things shrink when they get cold, yet the water clearly expanded enough to crack solid glass. The phenomenon raises immediate questions: Why did the water expand instead of shrink? How much force must the expansion have generated to crack glass? Does all matter expand when cooled? What is special about water? The visual evidence — the precise crack lines running along the bottle, the protruding ice plug, and the undisturbed frozen shape — makes the expansion undeniable and quantifiable, motivating the entire unit's investigation into temperature, thermal expansion, and the anomalous behaviour of water. The teacher presents a physical demonstration bottle (pre-prepared) alongside a labelled cross-section diagram showing: (1) liquid water molecules before freezing, (2) hexagonal ice crystal lattice after freezing with greater intermolecular spacing, (3) the direction of outward pressure on the glass walls, and (4) the resulting crack pattern.",
  "supportingPhenomena": "• The sagging overhead power line: Learners observe photographs of Kenya Power transmission lines — visibly slack and sagging on a hot Nairobi afternoon but taut and straight on a cold Kericho highland morning — prompting questions about how temperature affects the length of metal cables.\n• The stuck metal lid on a glass jar: A learner cannot open a metal lid on a glass jar of jam; running hot water over the lid for 10 seconds makes it open easily, illustrating differential thermal expansion between metal and glass and linking directly to the concept of coefficients of expansivity.\n• The bimetallic strip in a toaster or iron box: A bimetallic strip (brass and invar) straightens and bends visibly as it is heated and cooled, demonstrating that different metals expand by different amounts and that this difference can be harnessed to do mechanical work in thermostats and automatic switches common in Kenyan households.\n• Gap in railway tracks: Learners examine photographs of the Nairobi Commuter Rail and SGR tracks, observing deliberate small gaps left between rail sections — gaps that are tighter in the midday heat and wider on cold mornings — providing a compelling engineering application of linear expansion that learners can measure and calculate.",
  "drivingQuestion": "DRIVING QUESTION: Why did the sealed water bottle crack in the freezer — and what does this reveal about how all matter responds to changes in temperature?\n\nKICD KEY INQUIRY QUESTIONS:\n1. How does temperature affect the physical properties of materials?\n2. How is the expansion of solids, liquids, and gases applied in everyday life?",
  "storylineThread": "Lesson 1 — Encounter and Predict (The Cracked Bottle): Learners observe the pre-prepared cracked frozen bottle and a labelled diagram of the ice crystal structure. They record predictions about why the bottle cracked, whether all materials expand on cooling, and what factors might control the amount of expansion. The class co-constructs the Driving Question Board (DQB) with initial questions and a baseline particle model diagram.\n\nLesson 2 — Temperature Scales and Thermometers (Measuring the \"How Hot\"): Learners investigate different types of thermometers (liquid-in-glass, clinical, bimetallic strip) and their thermometric properties. They practice converting between Celsius and Kelvin scales using examples from Kenyan weather data (Nairobi vs. Marsabit temperatures). They revisit the DQB to add: \"What exactly is temperature measuring at the particle level?\"\n\nLesson 3 — Linear Expansion of Solids (The Stretching Rod): Learners conduct or observe a bar-and-gauge experiment using a metal rod heated with a Bunsen burner, measuring length change. They derive and apply the formula ΔL = αL₀ΔT, solving problems involving railway track gaps on the SGR and overhead cable sag for Kenya Power lines. They update their particle model to show increased vibration amplitude causing bulk expansion.\n\nLesson 4 — Superficial and Volumetric Expansion (From Length to Volume): Learners extend the linear expansion concept mathematically to area (β ≈ 2α) and volume (γ ≈ 3α) expansion, then investigate volumetric expansion of water experimentally using a flask-and-capillary-tube setup. Plotting a temperature–volume graph for water reveals the anomalous expansion below 4 °C — the key to explaining the anchoring phenomenon. Learners directly connect the water-expansion data to the cracked bottle.\n\nLesson 5 — Applications of Thermal Expansion (Engineering Solutions): Learners research and present real Kenyan applications: expansion joints on the Thika Superhighway, bimetallic strip thermostats in electric irons, fitting of metal tyres on wooden cart wheels, riveting in metal roofing. They evaluate how engineers calculate required gap sizes using the linear expansion formula and propose a design solution for a 10 m steel bridge beam in Kisumu exposed to a 35 °C seasonal temperature range.\n\nLesson 6 — Model Revision, Synthesis, and DQB Resolution (Explaining the Crack): Learners return to the anchoring phenomenon with full explanatory power — anomalous expansion of water, volumetric expansion formula, and the pressure generated against glass walls. They revise their cumulative particle model to integrate all lessons, resolve outstanding DQB questions, and produce a final annotated explanation poster connecting the cracked bottle to temperature scales, expansion coefficients, anomalous water behaviour, and real-world engineering design."
};

